I can tell you that your grass looks a lot greener from my side. As I said wanna write. In writing you can cover a much larger scope than you can visually.
And don't worry about the story. Starting and exposing your work to the public is a vital first step.
And don't be afraid to be more ambitious. You'll probably fall flat on your face the first few times, but that's just how it goes. It's what you have to do to improve.
And here's something I learned from my own (barely related) experience: Try not to hold stuff you are developing back, because you are afraid of wasting it. You will have many more and much better ideas in the future.

>>36842230
Try not to get trapped in a loop of self loathing. I know, it's easier said than done (trust me I fucking know), but try and focus not your problems themselves, but doing something about them.
Unfortunately drawing is a grueling and thankless task when starting out or working on further improvement. You should visit /dig/ here and lurk on /ic/. At least read the sticky over there.
I have been drawing for years (4 years, minus a long hiatus) and no day goes by without me feeling intimidated by all the stuff that is out there to learn and not even knowing where to begin.
Drawing is an abstract and ethereal thing that happens nowhere except in the artist's head. Everyone's brain is wired differently, so there is no silver bullet that'll cure all your issues. And unfortunately you will have to figure out most things by yourself, but you it will go an awful lot faster if others give you an idea where to look and then look.

Regarding grammar and trying to write the way you speak:

On some level you have to accept that you can't really control reading pace precisely, but you can bend it, and it"s not unusual to break some grammar rules to do it. The general guideline is that you should know what rule you're breaking and precisely what you mean to get out of it. That said, don't use commas for that purpose. The problem with commas is they have expectations associated with them. If I read a comma, I expect a clause to terminate. If it doesn't, I'm suddenly completely lost. It's like that feeling when you think there's one more stair. Instead, try to lean into changing overall sentence length or using fragments in places. Fragments may be just as grammatically incorrect as a comma splice, but in poetry you will see fragments and not splices. This is because periods in the case of fragments still mean the same thing as when they're used properly: "another sentence is starting now". As such, it's not confusing to read fragments.

You can also lean I to novel sentence structures. Some of my favorites are poly and asyndeton, where you either repeatedly use conjunctions and no commas or vice versa respectively. Polysyndeton reads super slow, asyndeton reads super fast, and neither is confusing.

If you're really into wanting control over the rhythm and "feel" of your writing, I strongly recommend reading Perrine's Sound and Sense for advice on how to do so. Further, I would suggest trying less to write the way you talk, and instead think back to the last time someone read to you and you liked the way they did it. Try to write the way you were read to.
